who was julian of norwich
in order to understand the figure and the message of this extraordinary english medieval mystic of the late fourteenth and early fifteenth century we have to glimpse briefly the historical background in which she lived
the fourteenth century was a period of many great mystics and saints like angela of foligno gertrude the great christina of stommeln raymond lull margaret ebner henry suso lidwina of schiedam also catherine of sienna and bridget of sweden who struggled for the reform of the church and the papacy
at the same time it was an unusually tumultuous age
it is estimated that more than a third of the population perished
there were many who considered the plague an eschatological sign of divine retribution
the impression that apocalyptic times were at the doors was strengthened by the longest conflict in the history of warfare lasting from 1337 to 1453
it was a conflict for the french throne between the royal house of valois who claimed the title of king of france and the house of anjou from england who claimed to be both kings of england and of france since they had their roots in the french regions of anjou and normandy
the english invasion was initially very successful in gaining new territories and much plunder but after the involvement of st joan of orleans in the battle and the solemn crowning of charles vii as king of france at reims they lost eventually much of what had been gained
naturally it ended in disaster
some of the crusaders were killed some were captured and the rest including the bishop returned home in disgrace
the failure of the papacy the corruption of the ecclesial hierarchy the abuse of indulgences and the crusade itself provoked general distrust in the visible institution of the church among the faithful on the continent as well as in england and prepared the ground for the precursors of the reformation
the xiv century england saw john wyclif preaching a reform of the church
he attacked the misuse of indulgences criticized the ecclesiastical hierarchy for seeking power and wealth and desired that the church return to the primitive simplicity of the gospel
besides he supported the translations of the bible into the english vernacular so that common people could understand it
scarcely a decade after wyclif’s death a bull was issued by boniface ix 1396 against wyclif’s followers called the lollards
in england they started to be fiercely persecuted and this culminated in the constitutions 1407 1408 of the archbishop of canterbury and chancellor of england thomas arundel who labelled them as traitors and heretics
unfortunately this constitution prohibited also the use of the bible and theological writings in english by lay people seeing in it an association with the heresy of wyclif
julian might have been a silent witness of their execution at a place known as the lollard pit
the city of norwich built around the river wensum and located in the county of norfolk near the coast of east anglia was an important port and england’s second largest city boasting 10 000 12 000 inhabitants in julian’s time
it was a flourishing centre of trade and religious life attracting a number of religious orders and movements including lollards who set up their houses there
this rome of england as norwich used to be called in the medieval times had 57 churches inside the city wall of which 31 still exist today
it confirms a popular saying that the city had a church for every week and a pub for every day
it is in this historical context that julian of norwich receives extraordinary visions on god’s love towards all people
amidst all the calamities raging around her book of revelations or showings as she herself often calls them must have had a counter cultural and revolutionary impact
with childlike simplicity and unwavering hope she comes to tell us that despite all evils god loves us and will make all things well again
in this way she succeeds in undermining the wide spread belief of the time namely that disasters and wars come from god who enraged by our sins sends chastisements upon the world
julian’s visions stand in complete opposition to this theology of god’s anger reminding us of the basic truth of the biblical revelation god is love 1 jn 4 16
that is the reason why julian can be regarded as one of the great pillars of western mysticism
thomas merton considers julian and john henry newman beatified by benedict xvi on 19 september 2010 the greatest english theologians
finally with her showings of love as far as it unveils god’s motherly operation of mercy and compassion for the world julian can be seen as a fourteenth century precursor of st faustina kowalska the great harbinger of the divine mercy in the xx century
st julian made an account of her revelations in two writings known as the short text and the long text
henceforth the long text will be referred to throughout the book as lt and the short text as st
throughout the text the quotations will be taken from the modern version of julian’s revelations based on the critical text by e colledge – j walsh julian of norwich
there are some bequests in wills that were probably made to her to support her living as an anchoress at st julian’s church in norwich
in one of these dated march 1393 it is said that the rector of st michael’s church at coslany in norwich roger reed left two shillings to julian anakorite
in the will of 1415 it is said that john plumpton a citizen of norwich left forty pence to the ankress in ecclesia santi juliani de conesford in norwice and twelve pence each to her serving maid and to her former maid alice
a year later in 1416 the countess of suffolk isabel ufford left a bequest of twenty shillings to julian
yet blomfield’s information is not thoroughly impossible
first of all we do not have any solid contrary proofs against julian’s old age and secondly blomfield’s text does not exhibit any confusion of julian who was considered a person of great holiness with another recluse who may have followed her way of life
there is another important witness to julian’s historicity given by her contemporary margery kempe of king’s lynn
